noun.description: An artificial underground passage, especially one built through a hill or under a building, road, or river.

verb.description: Dig or force a passage underground or through something.
examples: the insect tunnels its way out of the plant

verb.description: (of a particle) pass through a potential barrier.

origin: Late Middle English (in the senses tunnel-shaped net and flue of a chimney): from Old French tonel, diminutive of tonne cask. tunnel (sense 1 of the noun) dates from the mid 18th century.
